The interest in the quarries includes roughly 255 million tons of production.

Headlines.Author: Steven D. Jones
Headlines.Headline: Rising Timber Exports To China Buoy Northwest Economy

PARAGRAPH.#text: (This article was originally published Monday.) PORTLAND, Ore. (Dow Jones)--U.S. exports of wood products to China may roughly triple from a year ago as a building boom in the fast-growing country buoys an industry that has been hobbled since the housing bubble burst three years ago. The rise in exports to China is being felt across the Pacific Northwest, where timber companies are hiring and ports are handling increased volume. In the first 10 months of 2010, 2.1 million metric tons of logs and finished wood products were exported to China from the U.S., a figure that is on pace to reach nearly three times the 850,000 metric tons exported last year, according to the Piers trade data service of UBM Global Trade.

Even as prices for commercial and residential real estate have continued to tumble, timberland prices have remained strong. This, despite plummeting new-home starts and falling values for timber itself. As a result, timberland has become viewed as a safe-haven and an inflation hedge - driving ever more investors, large and small, to sink their money into stands of pine, maple and fir.
